    "μstep tooltip": "<strong>Microstepping</strong> divides each step of a stepper motor into smaller fractions, improving motion smoothness and resolution.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>It applies a sinusoidal current to the motor windings, reducing the step angle:<br><br><strong>Full step</strong> → 1.8°<br><strong>Half step</strong> → 0.9°<br><strong>1/4 step</strong> → 0.45°<br><strong>1/8 step</strong> → 0.225°<br><strong>1/16 step</strong> → 0.1125°<br><strong>1/32 step</strong> → 0.05625°<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>Smoother movement</strong>, less vibration, and higher precision.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Reduced torque</strong> at very small microsteps.<br>⚠ <strong>Precision limited</strong> by the quality of the driver and motor.<br>",
    "delay tooltip": "<strong>The delay between two steps</strong> is the waiting time between one pulse and the next sent to the stepper motor. This delay determines the motor's rotation speed and affects stability and torque.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>Each pulse commands a step of the motor. The time between two pulses (delay) is inversely proportional to speed:<br><br><strong>Long delay</strong> → Slower motor, more torque<br><strong>Short delay</strong> → Faster motor, less torque<br><strong>Ramp-up</strong> → Gradually reduces delay to accelerate without losing steps<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>Precise control</strong> of speed and torque.<br>✅ <strong>More stability</strong> with acceleration ramp management.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Too short delay</strong> can cause missed steps.<br>⚠ <strong>Too long delay</strong> reduces the motor's maximum speed.<br>",
    "speed tooltip": "<strong>The RPM speed of a stepper motor</strong> indicates the number of complete rotations per minute the motor can achieve. This speed depends on the pulse frequency sent to the motor and the number of steps per revolution.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>The speed is determined by the formula:<br><br><strong>RPM</strong> = (Pulse frequency in Hz × 60) ÷ (Steps per revolution)<br><br><strong>High frequency</strong> → Higher speed, lower torque<br><strong>Low frequency</strong> → Lower speed, higher torque<br><strong>Microstepping</strong> → Increases resolution but may reduce effective speed<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>Precise control</strong> of rotational speed.<br>✅ <strong>Adaptable</strong> to different applications by adjusting pulse frequency.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Too high speed</strong> can cause missed steps and lower torque.<br>⚠ <strong>Mechanical limitations</strong> due to inertia and applied load.<br>",
    "time tooltip": "<strong>The time to complete a full cycle</strong> refers to the time in milliseconds (ms) that a stepper motor takes to move from its starting position (0) to the maximum allowed distance. This depends on the motor's speed, step resolution, and acceleration profile.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>The total time can be calculated using:<br><br><strong>Time (ms)</strong> = (Steps required × Step delay) + Acceleration time<br><br><strong>Fast speed</strong> → Shorter time, but possible loss of steps<br><strong>Slow speed</strong> → Longer time, but more stable movement<br><strong>Acceleration profile</strong> → Helps optimize speed transition smoothly<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>Predictable motion</strong> for synchronized operations.<br>✅ <strong>Optimized efficiency</strong> by adjusting acceleration and speed.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Too short time</strong> can cause step loss and vibrations.<br>⚠ <strong>Too long time</strong> reduces system efficiency in time-critical applications.<br>",
    "max step tooltip": "<strong>Maximum travel per axis (Max Step)</strong> represents the maximum distance, in millimeters (mm), that a stepper motor can move along the X, Y, or Z axis in a complete work cycle. This value depends on the number of steps per revolution, the lead screw, or the belt system used.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>The maximum travel distance is calculated using the formula:<br><br><strong>Max Step (mm)</strong> = (Total steps per revolution ÷ Steps per mm) × Travel per revolution<br><br><strong>Larger step</strong> → More distance per step, but less precision<br><strong>Smaller step</strong> → Less distance per step, but higher precision<br><strong>Lead screw/belt ratio</strong> → Determines the conversion between steps and millimeters<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>Precise movement</strong> according to system requirements.<br>✅ <strong>Adaptability</strong> by adjusting lead screws, belts, or microstepping.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Physical limit</strong> imposed by the machine structure.<br>⚠ <strong>Cumulative error</strong> over long distances if calibration is not accurate.<br>",
    "coordinate tooltip": "<strong>Real-time position (Coordinates)</strong> represents the current location of the stepper motor in millimeters (mm) relative to the starting point (0). This value updates dynamically based on the last executed movement and is essential for precision control in CNC, 3D printing, and automation systems.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>The position is calculated using the formula:<br><br><strong>Position (mm)</strong> = (Current steps ÷ Steps per mm) + Initial position<br><br><strong>Incremental movement</strong> → Position updates after each step<br><strong>Absolute position</strong> → Calculated from a fixed reference (home position)<br><strong>Encoders or feedback</strong> → Ensure real-time accuracy in closed-loop systems<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>High precision</strong> tracking of motor movements.<br>✅ <strong>Essential for automation</strong> to maintain correct positioning.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Missed steps</strong> can cause position drift in open-loop systems.<br>⚠ <strong>Requires calibration</strong> to ensure absolute accuracy.<br>",
    "run tooltip": "<strong>Run Status Indicators</strong> represent the real-time state of the stepper motor using colored dots. These indicators provide a quick visual reference for the motor's operational status.<br><br><strong>🔹 How does it work?</strong><br>The system uses three colors to indicate different states:<br><br><strong>🟢 Green</strong> → The motor is actively moving.<br><strong>🟡 Yellow</strong> → The motor is waiting or under maintenance.<br><strong>🔴 Red</strong> → The motor is stopped and not performing any action.<br><br><strong>🔹 Advantages</strong><br>✅ <strong>Immediate visualization</strong> of motor status.<br>✅ <strong>Quick troubleshooting</strong> by identifying waiting or stopped conditions.<br><br><strong>🔹 Disadvantages</strong><br>⚠ <strong>Does not indicate errors</strong> beyond the basic state.<br>⚠ <strong>Requires additional diagnostics</strong> to determine specific issues.<br>",
